Stage 2 - Storming
Being in a team is like being in a relationship. At first, you may think someone is perfect and flawless.
But then you realise that they aren’t. Once you’re aware of their flaws, you either learn to embrace them or the relationship will end quickly.
Teams reached the Storming point of the team relationship when members have become aware of and are annoyed by other members’ characteristics.
In the storming stage, the reality and weight of completing the task at hand have now hit everyone.
The initial feelings of excitement and the need to be polite have likely worn off.
Personalities may clash. Members might disagree over how to complete a task or voice their concerns if they feel that someone isn’t pulling their weight.
They may even question the authority or guidance of group leaders.
Some team members may want to skip over the storming stage or try to avoid conflict at whatever cost.
Note that avoidance usually makes the problem grow until it blows up.
It is crucial to recognise conflicts and resolve them early on.
Strategy
- 1. Facilitate communication
Channel the team attention to communication, to discussion about all aspects of a project with a concentration on resolving issues.
Remind group members to listen for insights, since each person in the group holds some value else they wouldn’t be there.
Create an environment that is open and non-judgmental so that it is safer for people to share their ideas and opinions.
- 2. Embrace conflict
Remind others that good team dynamics won’t collapse because of conflict.
Frame disagreements as necessary and normal, and isn’t negative when it’s constructive.
Know that colleagues don’t have to agree all the time and take the conflict personally.
