### Notes:
What is a conflict?
A conflict is an expressed struggle between interdependent parties who perceive incompatible goals, scarce resources, and interference from the other party in achieving their goals.
The parties must rely on each other to reach their objectives, but since they cannot reach an agreement on what to do, they end up in a serious disagreement or even an argument.
- 1. Incompatible goals
This is when two parties think that their goals are mutually exclusive.
Example
- The Sales department offers quick paperwork processing to sweeten their deals. This requires the Accounts department to work overtime to process the transactions according to company guidelines.
- The Estates department wants to build a garden which will require the IT department to burst its budget to purchase additional WIFI equipment.
- 2. Scarce resources
The parties could be fighting for time, budget or support from bosses.
When there is not enough resources to satisfy both parties, one will always end up getting less and not enough.
Example
- A member takes up too much time at the meeting to seek approval, leaving little time for the other members.
- Comms is asking the Ops Manager to craft a statement regarding a work-place fire, while HR expects him/her to make a visit to the hospital to meet angry relatives first.
- 3. Interference/Obstacles
This happens when one party causes difficulty or blocks the other party from achieving his/her goal.
Example
A project team with a tight budget is instructed by the boss to use an expensive IT system.
The owner of a restaurant says no to the chef who is applying for day off to go to a product launch on New Year’s eve.
