### Notes:
Conflicts can be positive
When conflict happens people may feel uneasy or uncomfortable.
This may lead to one or both parties ‘backing down’ to avoid further communication about they needs and discussing solutions.
This avoidance is unhealthy for as long as the causes of the conflict are not removed, they are likely to cause future conflicts.
Instead, face the conflict and identify what CAN be done to foster better relationship and help people achieve their objectives.
Conflicts tell us:
- 1. Problems exist - Conflicts help people recognise that there is room for improvement.
- 2. What’s important to people - People highlights why certain things, such as a friendly atmosphere or a quiet environment is important to them. These are likely the key things to consider and tackle when attempting resolution.
- 3. Assumptions may be wrong - Conflicts can be caused by wrong assumptions of what people should do or know. Assumptions could be due to outdated information or a lack of communication.
- 4. A review is due –  If conflicts are caused by unclear direction, outdated practices or ineffective communication processes, it is time to review them.
Conflicts compel us to take actions on areas that are causing problems and will help make the team more cohesive and effective, if managed properly.
